  "prompt": "Were any real sets built for The Lego movie?",
  "response": "Yes, real, physical sets were indeed built for *The Lego Movie*, even though the film is primarily a CGI-animated feature. Despite the movie's digital nature, the filmmakers aimed to create an authentic Lego aesthetic that mimicked real-world Lego constructions. To achieve this, they built physical Lego sets and models as references for the animators. These physical models helped ensure that the textures, lighting, and overall look of the LEGO bricks in the movie were as realistic as possible.\n\nThe attention to detail was crucial in making the film feel like a stop-motion animation created with real Lego bricks, even though it was entirely computer-generated. The physical sets and models served as a guide for the digital artists, who then replicated the look and feel of real Lego pieces in the animated environment. This approach contributed to the film's unique and visually captivating style.",
